texts.short: The bucolic landscape at the point of arrival of this snowshoe hike is the worthy crowning of the itinerary.
texts.long: Castelir is a famous ski resort in the Alpe Lusia - Bellamonte area. Even though there is a large crowd of skiers at the starting point, after a few minutes of walking you enter a quiet environment. The itinerary takes place in a wide forest of fir and larch trees. In the final part, the vegetation gives way to the wonderful views of the Pale di San Martino and the Lagorai chain. The itinerary is generally used also by ski mountaineers.
texts.directions:
WAY UP Take the forest road behind the El Zirmo restaurant which, in constant ascent, connects Castelir to Malga Canvere. You move further and further away from the slopes through a wide forest with typical alpine huts. The slope is constant, but never particularly pronounced. Arriving at Malga Canvere, the forest thins out and the few pine trees embellish the view over the imposing Pale di San Martino and the Lagorai chain. The hut is not managed.

WAY DOWN On the same itinerary.
texts.publicTransit: Ski bus service from Predazzo to the Castelir ski area (Bellamonte).
texts.gettingThere: From Predazzo drive towards Passo Rolle. Once passed the village of Bellamonte, turn left and follow the directions to skiarea "Bellamonte - Alpe Lusia" (Castelir).
texts.parking: Many parking lots at the lift departure.
texts.safetyGuidelines:
The itinerary is not very difficult and there is no danger of avalanche 

 

THE 10 RULES FOR HIKERS 

  1. Prepare your itinerary beforehand
  2. Choose an itinerary that suits your physical abilities
  3. Choose suitable clothes and equipment
  4. Check the weather forecast
  5. Hiking by yourself is more risky; if this is the case, take a mobile phone with you
  6. Leave information about your itinerary and your expected return time
  7. If you are not sure about your itinerary, contact an Alpine Guide
  8. Pay attention to signposts and directions that you find along your way
  9. Do not hesitate in going back if you feel too tired
  10. In case of emergency call 112

Remember, snowpack stability is subject to sudden and unforeseeable changes and shifts. Always check the local avalanche before departure and make sure you gather all possible information concerning current conditions from the local Mountain Guides. GPS tracks are merely indicative of the more standard routes but must not be followed blindly without first checking current slope and terrain conditions. Correct orientation may be a problem at times along the higher stretches of this route due to fog or low cloud cover.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.

texts.short: An easy yet highly appealing route that winds its way through the woodlands of the “Enchanted Valley”. Indeed, don’t be surprised if you spot an elf or two peeping out from behind the trees!
texts.long: Just above the town of Palù del Fersina, the upper Valle dei Mocheni comes to an end in a striking amphitheatre of splendid peaks which, by the way, are also quite easily reached even in winter. Here we recommend a trek in the upper Valle del Laner where, thanks to the Sette Selle mountain hut (also open at weekends in winter), you’re always sure to find a pleasant place to rest and a bite to eat.
texts.directions: From the car park in the Frotten area, follow the paved road for about 100 metres until you reach the starting point of trail no. 325 on your right. Follow this trail in the direction for Erdemolo lake until it forks at an elevation of about 1,650 metres, here you take trail no. 343B that branches from your left and you follow the indications for the Sette Selle Mountain Hut. The alternative route no. 343 is not recommended during the winter months due to the presence of steeper and sometimes icy stretches in the woods.
texts.publicTransit: Bus no. 417 from Pergine to Palù del Fersina
texts.gettingThere: From Pergine Valsugana follow the Val dei Mocheni as far as Palù del Fersina then continue to the Battisti locality. Turn right at a junction on a curve (directions for Rifugio Lago Erdemolo and Rifugio Sette Selle) and after 500 metres you reach the large car park.
texts.parking: Spacious car park in the Frotten locality.
texts.startingPoint: The car park in the Frotten area of Palù del Fersina (1,504 m a.s.l.)
texts.safetyGuidelines:
The itinerary is quite safe from avalanche risk apart from a brief stretch at an altitude of 1,800 metres a.s.l. and just before the fork between trails 324/B and 324, where the route crosses the slopes of Mount Hoamonder.

Remember, snowpack stability is subject to sudden and unforeseeable changes and shifts. Always check the local avalanche bulletin (www.meteotrentino.it or any other service that suits your needs) before departure and make sure you gather all possible information concerning current conditions from the local Mountain Guides (www.mountime.it). GPS tracks are merely indicative of the more standard routes but must not be followed blindly without first checking current slope and terrain conditions.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. texts.equipment:
For all snowshoe treks, suitable apparel is strongly recommended. Temperatures can dip quickly and so garments should be warm and also be suitable for snowy conditions (such as waterproof Gore-Tex jackets). Furthermore, every group member should pack gloves, a cap, sun glasses and sun cream.

It’s also important to bear in mind that tight-fitting or insufficiently waterproof footwear can lead to frostbite.

We also strongly recommend that all members of the group pack an avalanche rescue kit consisting of avalanche transceiver, probe and shovel (this is also available for rent).

Ski poles can also come in quite useful and are therefore recommended.
texts.tip: Stop and have a peep into the "Gruab va Hardimbl" mine, close to the turn at 1,700 metres.

texts.short: This short and easy excursion winds its way along the right bank of the Venegia valley, in the presence of the Pale di San Martino Dolomites, and offers a truly spectacular panorama.
texts.long: The Val Venegia is rightly known as one of the most beautiful valleys in the Dolomites. This pleasant and sunny trek allows you to truly appreciate its charm as you make your way from the valley floor up to the crest that joins Valles Pass to Monte Mulaz, along open gently sloping terrain. The summit of Cima del Lago is also known as Cima Caladora.
texts.directions: From the car park at the mouth of the Val Venegia (in the Pian dei Casoni locality), you follow the road as far as the Malga Venegia farmhouse. From here you start climbing up the slope behind the farmhouse, crossing a narrow valley in an easterly direction and continuing upwards through the woods (there’s no marked trail along this stretch). The trees will slowly thin out as you climb and be substituted by the open slopes that lead you directly to the summit.
texts.gettingThere: From Predazzo follow the directions for Passo Valles until you reach the beginning of the valley of Val Venegia in the Pian dei Casoni locality.

texts.short: Easy hiking at the foot of the Pale di San Martino north chain
texts.directions: From the Passo Rolle, we climb up to Baita Segantini reaching 2,170 m above sea level. From here, we go down to the wide Val Venegia following the hairpin turns of the forest road up to the Pian della Vezzana. We then continue on flat ground to the Malga Venegiotta (closed in winter) and continue to go down to Malga Venegia, open in winter (info and reservations: 348 062 7886). We proceed down to Pian dei Casoni and, after crossing the parking lot, we take the bridge to the left. Going up, we follow the signs for Malga Juribello; initially the trail is narrow, but it then becomes wider and, through a beautiful forest, it exits onto the wonderful meadow pastures. Still climbing, we continue along the forest road towards south-east, (the point of reference is the electric line trellises). We then arrive at the Castellazzo chairlift and from there we’re shortly back to the starting point.

texts.long: Unforgettable snowshoeing through the forests of Nature Park Adamello Brenta, to the wonderful natural terrace at the rifugio La Montanara.

texts.short: Wonderful excursion at the foot of the Pale di San Martino, one of the most suggestive areas of Trentino.
texts.long: Very popular route, in a truly unique environment. Val Venegia looks like something out of a storybook; the trees covered with snow, the frozen Travignolo stream, the valleys that seem to be made of cotton wool and the view of the imposing rocky spur of Cimon della Pala, also known as the "Matterhorn of the Dolomites".
texts.directions:
WAY UP Walk toward the wood along the valley where the stream Travignolo flows; pass first Malga Venegia (1778 m), then Malga Venegiota (1824 m). Go on to the road which turns slightly right (south) leaving on your left-side some summer trails and walk uphill passing in front of the ropeway conveyor that serves Mulaz mountain hut. Right after leave on your left-hand another trail to Mulaz mountain hut and with the steepest part of the track with some bends you will reach Baita Segantini (2174 m). In a short time, going north, you will get to Costazza peak (2282 m).

WAY DOWN On the same itinerary.
texts.gettingThere: From Predazzo drive toward Passo Rolle: once passed the Visitors’ Centre of the Natural Park, turn left to Passo Valles. After about 3 km turn right (direction Val Venegia).
texts.parking: Leave your car in the big parking lot (called Pian dei Casoni) at the beginning of the valley.

texts.short: Relaxing itinerary in a beautiful forest of firs and Swiss pines, doable even after heavy snowfalls, as there is no danger of avalanches.
texts.long: The path on the slopes of the Corno Nero mountain offers beautiful views ranging from the nearby Corno Bianco Peak to the far Brenta Dolomites. Among the trees of the dense and silent wood you can also see the typical South Tyrolean villages of Redagno and Aldino.
texts.directions:
WAY UP Wear your snowshoes and leave the hotel Jochgrimm behind you, descending along the left side of the ski slope. At about 1900 m of altitude, on a tree on the left edge of the slope, you should be able to spot a sign pointing to path nr 4 to Malga Cugola. Follow the marks on the trees and after a while you will walk below a chairlift. Keep going through a wonderful wood of Swiss pines. The path continues through a gully and, after losing some altitude, reaches the Cugola Pass. From here slightly climb down on the other side (south), sometimes without snow, where you can find a stable on the right and Malga Cugola Alta on the left. 

WAY BACK Go up to Passo Cugola and take the path that, downhill, leads to the Malga Cugola Bassa. From here take the forest road on the right which, first uphill and then slightly downhill, leads to the valley station of the Doladizza chairlift. Climb up to the Isi Hütte (refreshment options) and continue uphill on the path that leads back to Passo Oclini along the ski slope.
texts.publicTransit: Skibus from Cavalese to Passo Oclini.
texts.gettingThere: From Cavalese or from Tesero take first the road to Passo Lavazè and then the road left which leads to Passo Oclini.
texts.parking: Many parking possibilities at Passo Oclini.

texts.short: Dos dei Branchi is a small peak that offers an extraordinary view over Val di Fiemme.
texts.long: The itinerary, not difficult, is suitable for everyone and takes place on large snow-covered ridges. The stretch that leads to Baito della Bassa is frequented, therefore tracks are visible almost all the time, while the next one that climbs to Dos dei Branchi is less known.
texts.directions:
From Pampeago take first the Agnello chairlift and reach Agnello mountain hut.

WAY UP From the top, on the right side (west) of the chairlift arrival (2180 m) a sign points the path which leads to La Porta and Baito della Bassa. With your snowshoes on, follow the big ridge, first descending slightly. Then, after a series of ups and downs, you will reach Baito della Bassa (2168 m). A short break at the hut allows you to admire the Pale di San Martino and the Lagorai chain. From here keep walking west, walking up to the small hill in front of you covered with mountain pines until the top of Dos dei Branchi (2274 m).

WAY BACK On the same itinerary.
texts.publicTransit: You can reach Pampeago with the skibus from Tesero.
texts.gettingThere: From Tesero take the road that leads to Passo Lavazè. When you reach Stava follow the directions to Pampeago.
texts.parking: There are many parking lots at the lifts station.

texts.short: Pleasant long excursion from Sicina, with a nice halfway stop at Malga Sass.
texts.long: The panoramic route on "the border" of Val di Fiemme allows you to reach the top of Monte Cogne. From up there you can admire the amazing view of the Lagorai chain, the Cembra Valley and the Pinè Plateau.
texts.directions:
WAY UP Walk up on the forest road, sometimes covered with snow, that going south leads to the plain of Bait del Manz (1290 m). Crossed the bridge, keep walking south on the forest road in the wood with some ups and downs and several hairpin turns. Ignore on your right-hand the two tiny roads to Malga Vernera and on your left-hand the path to Malga del Coston. Go on to the main forest road, with steeper parts, until Malga Sass (alpine diary) (1970 m 2,5 hours walk), already a good achievement.

From the Malga walk southern for a few hundred meters, then turn right in the wood on a track which leads to Passo di Mirafiori (passo Vasoni or la Bassa 2047 m). From this wide passage, between Monte Cogne and Pala delle Buse, climb up on the right side of the ridge, looking for less steep parts, and reach the cross of Monte Cogne, better known as Cimatti (2171 m).

WAY DOWN On the same itinerary (2,5 hours). Otherwise, from the peak go north, avoid walking along the crest, and descend down the ridge to the wood’s edge where you will find the path nr 468, coming from Malga Vernera. Descend toward north along a track which lowers into the wood and reaches first Malga Vernera Alta (1783 m), then a little church and right after Malga Vernera Bassa (1671 m, 1,5 hours). From here walk down to Baita del Monte Pat (1520 m), then leave the main forest road and turn right towards east in the wood. You will get to Bait del Manz: follow the road and you will return to the Fior di Bosco Farm House (1,5 hours).
texts.gettingThere: From the road that connects Val di Fiemme with Segonzano, take the road that goes up to Valfloriana. After passing the village of Sicina, follow the road to Fior di Bosco farmhouse (1,245 m).

texts.short: If you’re stretched for time but you don’t want to miss out on a charming trek across the snow, the highlands of the Viote are the perfect place for you.
texts.long:
The upland of the Viote is a kind of flat basin at the feet of the “Tre Cime” (Three Peaks) of Bondone and is easily reached both from Trento and the valley of Cavedine.

To the west these uplands are bordered by a long crest known as “La Rosta” which can be reached after an easy uphill trek and, although this route is suitable for all, it truly offers a spectacular view.
texts.directions:
You take off in a south/south-west direction along trail no. SAT 607 which skirts the bog until you reach the Malga Fragari farmstead. From here you take the path up along the Val d’Eva until you reach the Bocca di Vaiona at an elevation of 1,697 m a.s.l..

From here, turn right (north) along the crest following trail no. SAT 618 which leads right up to the highest point of “La Rosta”.

For your return trip, you can always take a shortcut by retracing your steps as far as the Val d’Eva and then cutting directly east through the woods until you emerge onto the open meadows below (see GPS track).

For all snowshoe treks, suitable apparel is strongly recommended. Temperatures can dip quickly and so garments should be warm and also be suitable for snowy conditions (such as waterproof Gore-Tex jackets). Furthermore, every group member should pack gloves, a cap, sun glasses and sun cream.

texts.short: A snowshoe walk not too demanding starting from San Martino di Castrozza and arriving to one of the most scenic spots overlooking the Pale di San Martino.
texts.long: The route starts very gently to then accentuate the elevation gain in the final part, with an effort amply repaid by the breath-taking view of the Dolomite group.
texts.directions: From the car park of the Sass Maor campsite (1,488 m asl), just before the start of the Colbricon Express Cableway in the Ces – Interski area, take the Valcigolera Forest Road keeping the Agility Forest Adventure Park on your left. The forest road is generally beaten because it is an itinerary used by the Troika with the horses, so in this first stretch of the route you can walk even without snowshoes. After a few hundred meters, at the first fork keep the right following Malga Valcigolera: after two hairpins, at the fork continue straight along the forest road, which returns to be slightly uphill until the bottom of the valley. At the Valcigolera bridge (1,654 m asl), continue on the left following the forest road, then turn right after about 20 meters, thus entering the valley keeping the Rio Cigolera on your right. At the end of the valley, follow the road that climbs towards the Malga along three hairpins with steep slope, to finally reach the Malga Valcigolera (1,883 m asl).

texts.short: An outing of intermediate difficulty along a circuit that takes you to Campo Carlo Magno, Malga Vigo, and Malga Zeledria.
texts.long: The itinerary runs mostly along a forestry road and then a trail as it winds through forests and pastures overlooking the Campo Carlo Magno Pass. This circuit does not involve a great deal of elevation gain, but it is not to be underestimated for its length. The itinerary crosses the ski slopes near Malga Vigo and Malga Zeledria. Both of these alpine farmhouses are excellent spots to enjoy a hot beverage or local alpine delicacies as you look out onto the amazing panorama of the Brenta Dolomites.
texts.directions: From Campo Carlo Magno descend 500 m towards Dimaro, reaching the Cross Country Ski Center. From the Cross Country Ski Centre 1.665m follow the main road for 100 metres towards Dimaro and after the Residence on the left take the forest road. Follow the road for about 2 km until you cross the bridge over Meledrio stream, 1.705 m (30 min). Continue along the road which now starts to steepen upwards towards the Piana delle Malghette , 1.776m. After reaching the Piana turn right immediately and climb the short distance up to Malga di Vigo, 1.803m (25 min). From the Malga descend on the sides of the ski slope, moving over to the right side of the stream, and passing close to the old cable car building, beyond which take the forest road that leads south towards Campo Carlo Magno(10 min). e route develops through the tall fir trees until the end of the road (25 min). Take the route with specific signs to Malga Zeledria in 30 min (refreshment bar and restaurant). Go down along the road with the hairpin turns towards Campo Carlo Magno; then go along the main road to the cross-country centre (25 min). To return to Campo Carlo Magno, it is possible to go backwards the first part of the suggested route.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Rio Falzè cross-country stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Campo Carlo Magno stop).
texts.gettingThere: Head up to the north from Madonna di Campiglio to Campo Carlo Magno pass along highway SS239. Take the first road to the left about 100 meters (300 feet) after the cross-country skiing center.
texts.parking: Paid parking at Campo Carlo Magno or free at the cross-country skiing center (on the right of the road towards Dimaro).
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Important: At the points where the itinerary crosses the ski slopes, we recommend keeping to the edges so as not to impede skiers coming down the slope.

Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip: Rest areas at Malga Vigo and Malga Zeledria

texts.short: A challenging winter outing with snowshoes or backcountry skis that goes from Campo Carlo Magno and past several alpine farmhouses to the intermediate station of the Grostè gondola lift.
texts.long: The itinerary first crosses the Campo Carlo Magno highland to Malga Mondifrà, an area that gets lots of sunlight all day long. You then head into a beautiful, dense forest of European spruce and silver fir as well as larch, where you will find Malga Vaglianella and Malga Vagliana as the forest begins to thin. Looking up, you will see the majestic south faces of Vagliana and Pietra Grande, while further to the south you will find the central section of the Brenta Dolomites and the Grostè ski runs, which you will encounter at the end of the itinerary near Rifugio Boch.
texts.directions: From Campo Carlo Magno descend 500m towards Dimaro, reaching the Cross Country Ski Center. From the Cross Country Ski Centre, 1.665m, follow route 6 to Malga Vaglianella 1.862m (55 min). Continue the ascend on the forest road for about 500 m, leave the road to continue on an ascend on the left side that allows to quickly reach a high altitude. For more tender paths, return (on the right side) on the road that quickly reaches Malga Vagliana, 1.976m (35 min). Turn right and climb the slope with a few zigzags up to the Sella di Vagliana, 2.038m, just below the top of the ski lift (10 min). From the Sella descend about a hundred meters to the left of the ski slope and at the end of the slope turn left. Continue over level ground to Pozza di Boch with the intermediate station of the Grostè cable car above, 2.070m (25 min). To return to Madonna di Campiglio follow the same route backwards or descend on the Grostè cable car from the intermediate station. It is possible to descend the slope skiing.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Rio Falzè cross-country stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Campo Carlo Magno stop).
texts.gettingThere: Head up to the north from Madonna di Campiglio to Campo Carlo Magno pass along highway SS239. From here go down about 500m to the cross-country skiing center.
texts.parking: Paid parking at Campo Carlo Magno or free at the cross-country skiing center.
texts.startingPoint: Campo Carlo Magno, Ski cross country center
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Important: Sections of the itinerary run along the cross-country skiing trails. We recommend you keep to the edges of the trail to not hinder oncoming skiers.

Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip:
Along the way, you will find three rest areas with food services: Ristoro Carlo Magno, Malga Mondifrà, and Rifugio Boch.

At the end of the excursion, you can return to Campo Carlo Magno using the gondola lift or skiing down the ski run.

texts.short: A challenging excursion for snowshoeing or ski mountaineering that goes from Madonna di Campiglio, past Malga Fevri, and along a stunningly panoramic false flat to Rifugio Graffer.
texts.long: This itinerary first heads into the woods along a groomed road followed by a trail. At the tree line, you will find a vast plateau and Malga Fevri with a stunning view of the Brenta Dolomites to one side and the Adamello glaciers to the other. The panorama here will take your breath away! From here, the itinerary continues along a false flat that is exposed to sunlight throughout the day until you reach Rifugio Graffer and the ski slopes. Take the lift (300m to the south) for the return trip.
texts.directions: From the station of the cable car Spinale reach (on foot) via Fevri and take the street north direction until the end. Here, on the right, take the path, continue uphill, paying attention to skiers, pass Piazza Imperatrice (30 min) and go on till Spinale 2 chairlift. Here leave the forest road and follow the itinerary in the wood in order to avoid the toboggan slope. Go on following the itinerary to reach Malga Fevri, 1.950m (40 min). Turn right and start crossing the plateau. e route proceeds gradually southwards to avoid the steep slope visible from a distance. Now turn right to reach Lago Spinale 2.036m, beyond which a short ascent leads to Campo Centener, 2.080m (40 min). Leave the high plateau on the left and, passing over a saddle, proceed keeping low in the little valley that leads further towards the east to a point where it is easier to pass the slope above. Climb up the slope to reach the Rifugio Graffer quickly, 2.270m (40 min). To return to Madonna di Campiglio follow the same route backwards, or go to the intermediate station of the Grostè cable car and take it down to the valley. It is possible to descend the slope skiing.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Spinale stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Spinale stop).
texts.gettingThere: Go to the south of Madonna di Campiglio and follow the signs for “Cabinovia Spinale”, the starting point for the itinerary.
texts.parking: Paid parking at the departure of the Spinale cable car.
texts.startingPoint: Madonna di Campiglio,  cable car Spinale
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Important: Sections of the itinerary run along the  alpine skiing runs and toboggan run. We recommend you keep to the edges of the trail to not hinder oncoming skiers.

Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip:
Rest area with food service at Rifugio Graffer.

At the end of the excursion, you can take the Grostè gondola lift at the intermediate station or ski down along the nearby ski run to get back down the mountain.

texts.short: An enjoyable stroll from Madonna di Campiglio to Malga Ritorto, where there is an exceptional view of the Brenta Dolomites.
texts.long: Excursion of intermediate difficulty along a snowy route in the wood around the village. The tour goes into a wood of firs, larches and bushes of mugo pine, near a pasture with the Malga Ritorto alpine hut. Malga Ritorto is in a place with an amazing view of the Brenta Dolomites eastward and the Adamello glacier southward/westward. Not to be missed a glimpse at sunset, when the rocks of the Dolomites becomes red.Thanks to the very good sunny exposure, Malga Ritorto is a natural terrace where enjoying the sun from morning to late afternoon.
texts.directions: Head south from the pharmacy in the center of town and continue along Via Adamello until you reach Pizzeria Pappagallo. Past the pizzeria, take the trail that runs flat (initially) from the far end of the parking area. When you reach the first crossroads (15 min.), turn right and follow the signs for Malga Ritorto as the trail begins to rise. Once you’ve completed the first steep climb through ample switchbacks in the trail (which is the most difficult section of the itinerary), you will reach a flatter area at an altitude of 1,660 meters (5,450 ft, 20 min.). From here the trail is less steep as you head south along a series of false flats to a clearing beneath Malga Ritorto (20 min.). Continue straight to the south and back onto a forestry road of accessible steepness, which will take you to your destination at an altitude of 1,746m (5,728 ft). Follow the same route in reverse to get back to Madonna di Campiglio.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Brenta Alta square stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Brenta Alta square stop).
texts.gettingThere: Enter Madonna di Campiglio south and follow the "Viale Dolomiti di Brenta" street up to the roundabout, before the limited traffic zone. Here take the Adamello street, go along it to the end of the street.
texts.parking: A small parking at the end of  the Adamello street, at the departure of the excursion, or an indoor play and display parking in Sissi square.
texts.startingPoint: From Madonna di Campiglio at the end of Adamello street (Pappagallo restaurant)
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low.

As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask
texts.tip:
Be sure to bring a camera.

Malga Ritorto is an excellent spot to enjoy a hot beverage or local alpine delicacies.

texts.short: Overlooking the Valsugana valley, we propose a sunny and panoramic route along gentle slopes with a final stretch leading along a crest which gives the entire excursion a truly Alpine feel.
texts.long:
The slopes above the town of Roncegno are amongst the most beautiful of the entire Valsugana, with dozens of farmsteads and mountain lodges dotting the land between the pastures and chestnut forests.

This is a very popular itinerary and takes you, without too much difficulty, to a truly rewarding and panoramic summit.

On your return trip you can always stop at the “Serot” mountain hut or the “Le Pozze” bar and restaurant, both of which offer fine food.
texts.directions: From the car park, go back along the same road for about 50 metres and you’ll find the start of trail no. SAT 372B which will take you to the Serot mountain hut in about 10 minutes. From there, follow the trail that climbs up towards the farmhouse in the Calvin locality and then continue in a north-easterly direction until you come across the path that leads west to the Val d’Ilba. Continue along the valley towards the saddle that joins Hoabonti peak and Monte Cola, once you reach the crest, turn sharply right and continue as far as the cross on the mountain’s summit.
texts.gettingThere: Take the SP65 road from Roncegno in the direction of Ronchi Valsugana until you reach the fork with sign-posts for “Le Pozze” restaurant and “Rifugio Serot”. The road that takes you up is paved butu rather narrow and can be particularly troublesome in the case of snow: make sure you have snow chains on board.
texts.parking: In the large car park beside the "Le Pozze" bar and restaurant
texts.startingPoint: The car park beside the "Le Pozze" bar and restaurant (1,431 m a.s.l.)
texts.safetyGuidelines:
The route is not completely free from avalanche risk so current local conditions must be checked before departure. It’s better to avoid the upper reaches of the itinerary (above 1,800 metres) in the case of fog or low cloud cover as it presents very few reference points and orientation may become a problem.

Remember, snowpack stability is subject to sudden and unforeseeable changes and shifts. Always check the local avalanche bulletin (www.meteotrentino.it or any other service that suits your needs) before departure and make sure you gather all possible information concerning current conditions from the local Mountain Guides (www.mountime.it). GPS tracks are merely indicative of the more standard routes but must not be followed blindly without first checking current slope and terrain conditions.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment:
For all snowshoe treks, suitable apparel is strongly recommended. Temperatures can dip quickly and so garments should be warm and also be suitable for snowy conditions (such as waterproof Gore-Tex jackets). Furthermore, every group member should pack gloves, a cap, sun glasses and sun cream.

It’s also important to bear in mind that tight-fitting or insufficiently waterproof footwear can lead to frostbite.

We also strongly recommend that all members of the group pack an avalanche rescue kit consisting of avalanche transceiver, probe and shovel (this is also available for rent).

Ski poles can also come in quite useful and are therefore recommended.

In the case of icy snow, it is recommended adding a pair of crampons to your gear.
texts.tip: At an elevation of 1,900 metres, once you’ve entered the Val d'Ilba, you’ll come across an abandoned mountain lodge which is the ideal spot for a short break.

texts.short: This excursion, although quite short, offers fantastic views of the Pale di San Martino and the Lagorai chain.
texts.long: Classic excursion for both snowshoes and ski mountaineering. After the first stretch in the pine and larch woods, the route develops on land without vegetation. The plateau at an altitude of 2,280 offers a fantastic view of the Pale di San Martino. Once you reach the Juribrutto Lake, nestled in a basin, you can admire the panorama of the Lagorai chain.
texts.directions:
WAY UP From Malga Vallazza (1935 m) walk up going north-west along the stream Vallazza, where you will find the summer trail nr 631 which leads to a plain at about 2150 m of altitude. Here you will find a sign pointing to Juribrutto lake: climb up going west and get to a small hill (2286 m), then keep walking south-west and on a slight descent you will reach the lake (2206 m)

WAY DOWN On the same itinerary.
texts.gettingThere: From Predazzo drive toward Passo Rolle: once passed the Visitors’ Centre of the Paneveggio Natural Park turn left to Passo Valles. Go on until you reach Malga Vallazza, before the top of the pass.
texts.parking: At Malga Vallazza, just before Passo Valles
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Tour not recommended in case of fog.

 

THE 10 RULES FOR HIKERS 

  1. Prepare your itinerary beforehand
  2. Choose an itinerary that suits your physical abilities
  3. Choose suitable clothes and equipment
  4. Check the weather forecast
  5. Hiking by yourself is more risky; if this is the case, take a mobile phone with you
  6. Leave information about your itinerary and your expected return time
  7. If you are not sure about your itinerary, contact an Alpine Guide
  8. Pay attention to signposts and directions that you find along your way
  9. Do not hesitate in going back if you feel too tired
  10. In case of emergency call 112

Remember, snowpack stability is subject to sudden and unforeseeable changes and shifts. Always check the local avalanche before departure and make sure you gather all possible information concerning current conditions from the local Mountain Guides. GPS tracks are merely indicative of the more standard routes but must not be followed blindly without first checking current slope and terrain conditions. Correct orientation may be a problem at times along the higher stretches of this route due to fog or low cloud cover.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment: Warm and waterproof winter clothes. Spare shirt, gloves, wool cap, sunglasses, sunscreen, water, snacks, hiking shoes and hiking poles.
texts.tip: The most trained and experienced can reach Juribrutto Peak.

Kompass – Val di Fiemme, Catena del Lagorai N° 618

texts.short: An enjoyable stroll through a coniferous forest to Malga Ritorto, where there is an exceptional view of the Brenta Dolomites.
texts.long: An easy outing for the whole family, this itinerary is entirely on packed snow and is mostly flat as it winds through a stunning, tall forest of fir and larch. The landscape changes near the malga (a mountain farmhouse) as the forest gives way to mugo pine and pastureland. The panorama from Malga Ritorto is exceptional as you look out over the Brenta Dolomites mountain range. The view is especially stunning at dusk, when the setting sun colors the rocky spires pink. Thanks to its orientation, this is a particularly great spot to enjoy many hours of sun, from early morning till late into the afternoon. The restaurant and café here is an excellent place to enjoy a hot beverage or local alpine delicacies.
texts.directions: From Madonna di Campiglio, by cable car Colarin Patascoss, you reach Patascoss area. From the cableway station, 1.750m , descend on the right side of the run, paying attention to skiers, for about 100m till you reach the road and enter a firs wood. Continue on a flat road for about 2 km till you reach the wide land of the mountain hut from where the panorama on the Dolomites is majestic (40 min). To return follow the itinerary vice versa to descend to Madonna di Campiglio by lift. e most trained can descend following the instruction of itinerary n.2 that brings directly to town.
texts.publicTransit: To reach Colarin: served by the Madonna di Campiglio ski bus (Colarin stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line. To reach Patascoss: Campiglio express lift, Colarin - Patascoss section
texts.gettingThere: In Madonna di Campiglio, park your car at the Colarin parking lot, then take the Pinzolo-Campiglio Express gondola lift to Patascoss.
texts.parking: Free parking at Colarin lot, near south tunnel entrance.
texts.safetyGuidelines: Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip: Be sure to bring a camera. Two refreshment points are available along the way: the Patascoss refuge at the start, and the Malga Ritorto upon arrival.

texts.short: A marvelous loop of intermediate difficulty through Val Brenta and Vallesinella, two valleys running through the heart of the Brenta Dolomites and past the stunning Cascate di Mezzo (middle falls).
texts.long: The itinerary runs along snow trails and forestry roads and through forests of European silver fir, interspersed with clearings and alpine farmhouses, alongside crystal-clear streams to a stunning clearing at Malga Brenta Bassa. Here, there is a breathtaking view of the Dolomites and the west face of Crozzon di Brenta overlooking the valley. The highest point of the outing is at the Vallesinella Cascata di Mezzo, which freezes in winter and makes for some truly thrilling ice climbing.
texts.directions:
From Prà de la Casa area continue to Malga Brenta Bassa along the forest road for about 30 min. From Malga Brenta Bassa , 1.256m, follow the forest road that develops among woods of firs and conifers till you reach the intersection that brings to the path for the Vallesinella di Mezzo waterfalls (60 min).

After crossing the characteristic wooden bridge you can admire the amazing view on the frozen waterfalls. To return follow the itinerary vice versa till the starting point.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Hoptel alla Posta stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Sant'Antonio di Mavignola stop).
texts.gettingThere: From Sant’Antonio di Mavignola, to the south of Madonna di Campiglio, follow the signs for “Val Brenta”. Take the downhill road across the bridge over the Sarca river to Prà della Casa. Park your car here and continue on foot.
texts.parking: Parking is available free of charge in Prà de la Casa.
texts.safetyGuidelines: Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip: Be sure to bring a camera.

texts.short: A gradually rising, sunlit itinerary up to a vast clearing at Milegna and the nearby Malga Ritorto. The route offers a beautiful view of the Rendena Valley to the south, the Brenta Dolomites to the east, and the Adamello mountain range to the west.
texts.long: An excursion of intermediate difficulty along forestry roads and trails through a wooded area to Milegna. Here, there is a vast pastureland overlooking the entire Rendena Valley to the south and on to the southernmost foothills of the Alps. The truly stunning panorama extends from the Brenta Dolomites to the east to the Adamello mountain range to the west. The itinerary continues to the north until you reach Malga Ritorto. Thanks to its orientation, this is a particularly great spot to enjoy many hours of sun, from early morning till late into the afternoon.
texts.directions: From Madonna di Campiglio or S.A. di Mavignola on the SP 239 you reach Paluac area, where you can park. From the parking lot you can take the forest road, that ascends towards north close to the Masi di Paluac and then gradually takes to the Milegna pasture (40 min). Here the road becomes steeper and, crossing the pasture, it arrives to Casa Capot. e path continues on a flat pavement reaching shortly Malga Ritort (50 min), 1.747m. To return follow the itinerary vice versa till the starting point.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Fratè stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Fratè stop).
texts.gettingThere: Go to Paluac (400 meters past Fratè) along highway SS239, between Madonna di Campiglio and Sant’Antonio di Mavignola. Parking is available here.
texts.parking: Park along the highway near the start of the itinerary.
texts.startingPoint: S. Antonio di Mavignola, Paluac area

Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.

texts.short: A pleasant stroll through the woods to the beautiful Nambino Lake, a place of unparalleled peace and tranquility immersed in nature.
texts.long:
An excursion of intermediate difficulty but accessible to all and that runs through a beautiful forest along a trail that winds its way gradually up the mountain.

The destination is a natural amphitheater with an alpine lake of rare beauty, which is covered in snow and ice in winter. Overlooking the lake is a typical alpine lodge in this enchanting setting in which to enjoy local alpine delicacies as you gaze out over this tranquil scene.

It is also an exceptional spot from which to admire the Brenta Dolomites, particularly at dusk, when the setting sun colors the rocky spires pink.
texts.directions: From the center of the town head north and after 300m from the exit nord of the tunnel (at Hotel Cristal Palace) take the public road left and follow for about 500m until you reach Piana di Nambino area, 1.635m (15 min). After the tunnel turn right passing along the ex Malga Nambino and after the last buildings take the forest road that leads to the start of the path which climbs the final steep part (15 min). Passing the start of the cable car the route begins to climb and crosses the stream. After a few turns and a dense pine wood you exit on a flat ground at the outlet of the lake, from where the Refuge, 1.770m, is soon reached (20 min). To return to Madonna di Campiglio follow the same route backwards
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Hotel Cristal Palace stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Hotel Cristal Palace stop).
texts.gettingThere: Arriving from the south through the Rendena Valley along highway SS239, pass Madonna di Campiglio, then turn left 200 meters (220 yards) after exiting the tunnel. Follow the signs for “Lago di Nambino”.
texts.parking: Free parking in "piana di Nambino" area, the starting point of the excursion.
texts.safetyGuidelines: Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip:
Be sure to bring a camera.

The itinerary is exposed to the sun during the morning hours.

You won’t want to miss the thrill of an evening outing followed by dinner in the lodge.

texts.short: A beautiful circular tour takes us to one of the most attractive parts of the subgroup of the Cime di Rava range, namely, the hollow that conceals the Laghetti dell'Inferno, not far from the Caldenave plateau. The route described here is little used in winter. Along the high stretch you can rarely find a beaten track, therefore a minimum sense of direction is required. Difficulty: Average
texts.directions: From Località Tedon follow the summer trail that climbs up to Rifugio Caldenave (SAT trail 332), as far as the large plateau at an altitude of 1770m. Here, go to the left, crossing the small bridge of Caldenave and follow the signs to Laghetti dell'Inferno. At an altitude of 1900m, when you see a rocky crag under which the trail passes along the flat (an alternative route to get directly to the Laghetti dell'Inferno), continue uphill into the sparse larch woods. At the edge of the woods, go diagonally to the left to get to the Aia dela Pesa peak (a great vantage point). From here, go down into the hollow of the Laghetti dell'Inferno (steep slope) and continue in a north-west direction towards the Baita di Lastei. You can now freely descend into the woods (be careful to go around some rocky mounds) until you meet the flat trail that connects the Piana di Caldenave to Malga Nassere (alpine dairy). When you get to the latter, following the signs to Rifugio Carlettini, you can quickly go back down the valley to arrive not far from the starting point.
texts.gettingThere: From Strigno in the Valsugana, go up the Val Campelle as far as the mouth of the Val di Caldenave (Località Tedon – signs to Rifugio Caldenave).
texts.parking: Free car park (about 20 parking spaces)
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Be careful when choosing the route for the first stretch of the descent: the slope that goes down from Aia della Pesa to the Laghetti dell'Inferno is rather steep and has several small rocky crags to get around.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment: The usual snowshoe touring equipment. An avalanche transceiver, a shovel and a probe are recommended.

texts.short: Long but easy itinerary among the pretty forest of fir trees. Almost the entire walk follows a well-marked forest road and there is no danger of avalanche.
texts.long: This little-frequented route allows you to immerse yourself in the silence of nature, interrupted only by the noise of the Rio delle Stue and the wind among the branches of the fir trees. Your effort will be rewarded by a lonely environment of rare beauty, where Stellune peak overlooks the valley.
texts.directions:
WAY UP From the bridge follow the forest road (nr 318) which runs along the left-side of the stream Stue. The road gets into a beautiful spruce firs wood and reaches a clearing where Malga Stue Bassa is located (1400 m): from here you have the sight of the impressive peak of Montalon. Keep walking on the same road, ignoring all the deviations, and once passed Malga Stue Alta you reach Malga Cazzorga (1845 m).

WAY DOWN On the same itinerary
texts.gettingThere: From Molina di Fiemme, follow the sign to Passo Manghen and drive until you reach Ponte Stue (1.252 m), where the snow clearing ends.
texts.parking: Leave your car before or after the bridge.
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Almost the entire walk follows a well-marked forest road and there is no danger of avalanche. 

 

THE 10 RULES FOR HIKERS 

  1. Prepare your itinerary beforehand
  2. Choose an itinerary that suits your physical abilities
  3. Choose suitable clothes and equipment
  4. Check the weather forecast
  5. Hiking by yourself is more risky; if this is the case, take a mobile phone with you
  6. Leave information about your itinerary and your expected return time
  7. If you are not sure about your itinerary, contact an Alpine Guide
  8. Pay attention to signposts and directions that you find along your way
  9. Do not hesitate in going back if you feel too tired
  10. In case of emergency call 112

Remember, snowpack stability is subject to sudden and unforeseeable changes and shifts. Always check the local avalanche before departure and make sure you gather all possible information concerning current conditions from the local Mountain Guides. GPS tracks are merely indicative of the more standard routes but must not be followed blindly without first checking current slope and terrain conditions. 

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment: Warm and waterproof winter clothes. Spare shirt, gloves, wool cap, sunglasses, sunscreen, water, snacks, hiking shoes and hiking poles.
texts.tip: Along the way the passage of the Vaia storm (October 2018) is visible. The wolf has spontaneously returned to living in Val Cadino.

texts.short: An enjoyable winter outing of intermediate difficulty alongside the Campo Carlo Magno cross-country trails to Malga Mondifrà and Malga Vaglianella.
texts.long:
This snowy loop crosses the vast Campo Carlo Magno highland. Starting from the cross-country trails, the itinerary heads out into the open beyond the woods in an area that gets lots of sun all day long. Once you have passed Malga Mondifrà, the trail heads into a beautiful, dense forest of European spruce and silver fir as well as larch. When you reach Malga Vaglianella, head down through the woods in a loop that will take you back to the start.

Malga Mondifrà is a great place for a relaxing break as you enjoy a hot beverage or local alpine delicacies.
texts.directions: This circular route starts from the Cross-Country Ski Centre in Campo Carlo Magno. Follow the marked route, taking care not to be on the cross-country ski slopes. e route goes over an initial undulating path to Malga Mondifrà, 1.632m (25 min), where it leaves the wide pastures and goes into the forest. Climb easily up the ridge on the left side of Valgelada until you reach Malga Vaglianella , 1.862m (30 min). From the Malga, which is the outer limit of the circuit, head south and descend the Tovo di Vagliana, at the end of which you meet the cross-country ski slope again (25 min). Follow the same track used for the outward journey back to the Cross-Country Ski Centre (25 min).
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Rio Falzè cross-country stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Campo Carlo Magno stop).
texts.gettingThere: Head up to the north from Madonna di Campiglio to Campo Carlo Magno pass along highway SS239. From here go down about 500m to the cross-country skiing center.
texts.parking: Paid parking at Campo Carlo Magno or free at the cross-country skiing center.
texts.startingPoint: Campo Carlo Magno, Ski cross country Center
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Important: Sections of the itinerary run along the cross-country skiing trails. We recommend you keep to the edges of the trail to not hinder oncoming skiers.

Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.

texts.short: An itinerary of intermediate difficulty, but without an excessive elevation gain, through the Brenta Valley in the heart of the Brenta Dolomites.
texts.long: A mostly flat excursion that alternates between snowy trails and forestry roads through a forest of lovely European silver fir trees interspersed with open areas, clearings, and alpine farmhouses. The itinerary runs alongside crystal-clear streams of the Brenta Valley to a beautiful clearing at Malga Brenta Bassa, where there is a stunning view of the Dolomites and the west face of Crozzon di Brenta overlooking the valley.
texts.directions: From S.A. di Mavignola reach Prà de la Casa area, where you can park. Or starting on foot from S. A. di Mavignola, passing through Maso Doss (30 min) , descend along the path and cross the Sarca di Campiglio river. Walk on the left side of Val Brenta and gradually ascend to the Pinzolo-Campiglio Express. After short time you reach Prà de la Casa area (45 min). Continue along the forest road passing through a characteristic white firs wood; once left the crossroad to Valagola on the right side continue to Malga Brenta Bassa (30 min) from where it opens an amazing viewpoint on the Brenta Dolomites. Turning on the right side you get back in the woods, cross the Sarca river and reach Malga Fratte (20 min). From here, quickly and in descend, you return to Prà de la Casa area.

texts.short: An uphill itinerary from Sant’Antonio di Mavignola to Clemp, where there is an extraordinary vista point overlooking the Rendena Valley, the Brenta Dolomites, and the Adamello mountain range.
texts.long: An excursion of intermediate difficulty that winds up steeply through the woods to Clemp, which overlooks the valley below and out across the Adamello mountain range to the west and the Brenta Dolomites to the east, both of which form the Rendena Valley in the middle. Because of its strategic position, the area of Clemp was selected for the construction of an ancient fortress that was used as an Austrian outpost during World War I. The remains of this structure are visitable to this day. The area also features several characteristic mountain huts known locally as “case da mont”.
texts.directions: From the town of S.A. di Mavignola you reach Parco ai Sas (coming from Madonna about 200m after the crossroad of Val Brenta turn right, coming from south about 200m after the supermarket turn left). Once crossed the park you take the forest road, towards north till its end (30 min). When you get close to the aqueduct take the path on the left, ascending with various turns in the woods till Forte Clemp and the area with the same name (45 min), 1.540m. To return to S.A. di Mavignola, follow the itinerary vice versa.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (S.Antonio di Mavignola stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (S.Antonio di Mavignola stop).
texts.gettingThere: Go to Parco ai Sass in Sant’Antonio di Mavignola along highway SS239 through the Rendena Valley. Arriving from the north, turn right approximately 200 meters (220 yards) after the intersection for Val Brenta. From the south, turn left approximately 200 meters (220 yards) after the supermarket.

texts.short: A not too difficult informative circular tour, which offers extensive views of the Altopiano di Folgaria and much more: from the peak of Monte Maggio views sweep from the Pasubio to the Brenta Dolomites and the Lagorai mountain range.
texts.long:
The Passo Coe area is an ideal ground for snowshoeing: a broad plateau with magnificent woods alternates with sunny pastures, where most of the peaks can be reached without too much difficulty. The only drawbacks are the newly created ski trails towards Costa d'Agra, which have effectively stopped tours in the northern area.
Luckily, further south, towards the slopes of Monte Maggio, you can still find quieter areas appreciated by those who more discreetly move among nature...
To illustrate the most interesting aspects of the area, we have involved our colleague Mario Martinelli, who is very familiar with these places that he has known for a lifetime.
Together we have followed a great circular route, chancing upon animal tracks, “out-of-season” flowers, artefacts from the war and much more... An example of how, also in winter, the mountains covered at a walking pace offer a multitude of surprises and stories to tell.
Such treasures make us think that, perhaps, it should be given greater consideration by those who are involved in developing tourism in the local area.
texts.directions:
From Malga Zonta head north to Malga Melegna (alpine dairy at 1550m). Along this stretch, you can take an interesting diversion as far as the former NATO base, not far away. From Malga Zonta head towards the eastern ridge of Monte Maggio (continuing to the north), following the cross-country ski trail for a stretch, and then freely entering the woods (a stretch of the summer path that is not easily identifiable).
When you get close to the mountainside, where the ground becomes steeper, go uphill to the fork that separates the peak of Valscura (on the left) from Monte Maggio. From the fork, go along the easy ridge westwards, keeping the huge cross at the summit as a point of reference.
On the descent, take the clearly marked paved road that returns to Passo Coe, which takes you back to the cross-country ski trails and bends round to the south-east and back to Malga Melegna. From here, you can return to the starting point in just a few minutes.
texts.gettingThere: From Folgaria (which can be reached from the Vallagarina or the Valsugana), go to Passo Coe and go downhill for about 2.5 kilometres as far as the car park at Malga Zonta (signposted to Base Tuono).
texts.parking: Free car park (about 10 parking spaces)
texts.safetyGuidelines:
If there is a very abundant snow cover, the slope below the fork, although short, may be subject to avalanches. In this case, it is advisable to follow the safest and always well-beaten descent route.

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment: The usual snowshoe touring equipment. An avalanche transceiver, a shovel and a probe are recommended.

The itinerary winds above Madonna di Campiglio through tall forests of fir and larch.

To return to Madonna di Campiglio follow the same route backwards.

texts.short: A fairly accessible excursion for snowshoeing or ski mountaineering that goes from Monte Spinale along a stunningly panoramic false flat to Rifugio Boch.
texts.long: This snowy itinerary along the tree line features a truly stunning panorama. The trail runs from Monte Spinale along a false flat that gets lots of sunlight throughout the day and takes you to Rifugio Boch. Here, you will find the ski runs and the intermediate station of the Grostè gondola lift, which may be used for the return trip.
texts.directions: From Madonna di Campiglio take the Spinale cable car to the top of Monte Spinale. From the Rifugio Dosson (Chalet Fiat) go down eastwards alongside the ski slope for about 300m, where descending gradually rightwards you reach the dell below (15 min). Continue trending south following a section in common with route 10, reaching Lago Spinale and then, beyond that, Campo Centener, 2.080m (25 min). From here turn left and head north across the big flat zone, descending a slight ridge towards the Grostè ski area. After a few dozen meters of descent a ground leads to the forestry road normally used by tracked service vehicles. A short slightly rising section leads to the intermediate station of the Grostè cable car, 2.070m (20 min). To return to Madonna di Campiglio follow the same route backwards, or descend in the cable car to Fortini.
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Spinale stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Spinale stop).
texts.gettingThere: Go to the south of Madonna di Campiglio and follow the signs for “Cabinovia Spinale”. Park your car here and take the lift to the starting point for the itinerary.

texts.short: An enjoyable winter stroll for the whole family that can be done on foot or with snowshoes. The itinerary runs alongside the Campo Carlo Magno cross-country trails to Malga Mondifrà.
texts.long:
An easy outing for the whole family through the Campo Carlo Magno ski area for alpine and cross-country skiing.

This itinerary, of insignificant elevation gain, is out in the open and, for the most part, beyond the woods, so it is exposed to sunlight throughout the day.

Malga Mondifrà is in a tranquil setting overlooking the cross-country trails and is a great sport for a relaxing break as you enjoy a hot beverage or local alpine delicacies.
texts.directions: From Madonna di Campiglio reach Campo Carlo Magno till Fortini area, where you can park. From the town center go north and, on the sidewalk, walk towards Campo Carlo Magno. At the start of the Grostè cableway, in Fortini area, cross the parking lot and reach the characteristic field of Campo Carlo Magno. Go over it walking on a flat surface, close to the natural little lake and the ruins of Malga del Campo on the left side. Afterwards, passed the ski runs cross (paying attention to skiers), take the forest road (25 min) on the left side and follow it with no important difference in height till Malga Mondifrà, 1.630m (25 min). Follow the itinerary vice versa
texts.publicTransit: Served by the Madonna di Campiglio Skibus (Grostè cablecar stop) or the Trentino Trasporti bus line (Grostè cablecar stop).
texts.gettingThere: Reach loc. Fortini near the Grostè cableway, 1 km northwards Madonna di Campiglio along the main road SS239. To reach the cableway coming from Pinzolo, take the tunnel at the beginning of Madonna di Campiglio - avoiding the centre of the village - and go on towards Campo Carlo Magno for about 1 k after the tunnel exit. Coming from Dimaro, instead, pass Campo Carlo Magno and, after about 800 meters, arrive at the Grostè cableway.
texts.parking: Big free parking at the departure of the Grostè cableway.
texts.safetyGuidelines:
Important: Sections of the itinerary run along cross-country skiing trails and, to some extent, alpine skiing runs. We recommend you keep to the edges of the trail to not hinder oncoming skiers.

Experience walking along irregular mountain trails is recommended. In the event of fresh snow, snowshoes are also recommended. Be careful of ice when temperatures are particularly low. As you might imagine, the accessibility of these mountain trails depends entirely on the conditions found at any given time, such as the weather and other natural and environmental conditions. Therefore, before you set out, you should check the status of the trail by contacting alpine guides, lodge operators, or the local tourist office or park information office.
texts.equipment: Appropriate winter clothing, hiking boots, walking poles and instep crampons or snowshoes, water bottle or thermos flask.
texts.tip:
If you would like to give cross-country skiing a try, you may rent equipment and take lessons at the nearby Campo Carlo Magno cross-country skiing center.

Families with young children will want to bring a sled for the snowy hills near Campo Carlo Magno Pass.

texts.short: Right at the feet of Passo Manghen, there is a small alpine valley, beautiful in every season.
texts.long: The woods that frame the road that crosses Val Cagnon, become a fairy tale-like scenario when the it starts snowing. This itinerary is feasible both with snowshoes and skis and isn’t difficult, given the gentle incline of the whole path.
texts.directions: Park the car near Malga Baessa and then start walking on the main road until the Malga Valtrighetta pasture. Then bend in the track on the left that passes right under the alpine farm, keep walking towards Malga Cagnon di Sopra, passing by Malga Casabolenghetta, Malga Casabolenga and Malga Cagnon di Sotto. The return can be done following the same route.
texts.gettingThere:
From the SS47 main road, exit in Borgo Valsugana or Castelnuovo and follow the signs to "Telve - Passo Manghen".

Drive for almost 16 km and you will reach Malga Baessa.
texts.parking:
At the parking of Malga Baessa.

If the provincial road is open, you can park near Malga Valtrighetta and shorten the itinerary.
texts.safetyGuidelines:
The stability of the snow cover is subjected to sudden and unpredictable changes.

Always check the avalanche bulletin (www.meteotrentino.it) and ask about the weather conditions in the local Alpine Guides offices.

The gpx tracks are just an approximation of the suggested route and can not be followed without a preliminary evaluation of the current situation of the snow and the ground.

texts.short: Round trip in the evocative woods of Monte Zugna between the memories of the Great War and the wide views on Vallagarina
texts.long: This walk winds through beech and pine woods, starting from the back of the Italian army placement in the First World War up to the front line near the Austro-Hungarian trenches. The return path winds through the trenches dug by soldiers, passing in front of the cemetery of S. Giorgio and then back up towards Rifugio Zugna
texts.directions: The itinerary starts in front of the door of the shelter, taking a downhill road (wooden bar). Up to the Trincerone area, about half way, the track, called "Sentiero del Sinel" is indicated by white square trail markers with blue mark at the center, drawn on the trunks of the trees. From the Trincerone trench, the itinerary goes along the road to the cemetery of S. Lazzaro and then proceeds into the woods alongside the roadway (on the left, going up to the shelter) unraveling inside the remains of a trench. Once you’ve reached the road again, near a hairpin bend, continue on the opposite side along the road that leads to the cemetery of S. Giorgio and from here, following the signs of the Peace Path, along a characteristic mule track up to the mountain refuge
texts.gettingThere: From Rovereto follow the signs to Campana dei Caduti, going up to the hairpin bend above the hamlet Porte di Trambileno. From here continue on the SP89 until the next hamlet, Albaredo. Turn right at the entrance to the village (signs to Rifugio Zugna).
texts.parking: There are parking lots near the shelter
texts.safetyGuidelines:
• Pay attention in the case of heavy snowfall which can create dangerous accumulations even in areas considered not subject to the risk of detachment.
  • It is always advisable to consult the avalanche bulletin, possibly integrating it with the request for information to qualified subjects.
  • With low temperatures pay attention to ice which can be, even with little snow, very dangerous. Avoid the sections entirely covered by ice sheets, especially if sloping and close to exposed stretches.
  • In winter, the opening of shelters and points of support can not be guaranteed. Check availability in advance by contacting the facilities directly. 

 

Please note that the practicability of the itineraries in a mountain environment is strictly linked to the contingent conditions and is therefore influenced by natural phenomena, environmental changes and weather conditions. For this reason, the information contained in this page may have changed. Before leaving for a tour, make sure the path you will approach is still accessible by contacting the owner of the mountain hut, the alpine guides or the visitor centres of the nature parks, the info offices of the local tourist board.
texts.equipment:
• Take warm clothing with you, it must protect you from the cold but must not be too bulky or heavy. Do not forget to put a spare t-shirt in your backpack as wearing wet or damp clothes can be very annoying pausing with low temperatures.

texts.short: Wide round ring on the vast plateau of the Lessini Mountains
texts.long: You are in Lessinia, a vast plateau characterized by gentle slopes and undulating hills that unites the Trentino with the Veneto. Here, where in winter the pastures cover themselves with snow, turning into a soft and candid sea, you can snowshoeing or cross-country skiing, while in the warm season, when the meadows cover with flowers, you can fully enjoy this landscape, walking the numerous paths on foot or exploring these places riding a bicycle. Let your gaze wander through the green of the meadows, pastures and woods, the blue of the sky and the white of the Lessinia stone, and enjoy the view over the Vallagarina and the Carega-Piccole Dolomiti mountain group that you can admire during this excursion , near the Rifugio Castelberto
texts.directions: From Sega di Ala, the route follows the forest road (Strada delle Malghe) which passes just below Malga Maia and continues then towards Malga Lavacchione. Just before Malga Revoltel. near a hairpin bend, leave the forest road followed so far and proceed for a short stretch in the small valley, then continue going left with two hairpin bends. From here head towards Malga Coe di Ala, after which you cross the road that leads to the left towards Rifugio Castelberto. Alternatively, turning right, you can proceed along the road directly to Malga Lessinia and then, after about 400m, turn right towards Malga Campo Revolto and Malga Lavacchietto until you rejoin the Malghe road that leads to Località Sega di Ala.

texts.short:
Nice excursion in the Lagorai, safe ,except for the last part in proximity of the top, in case of heavy snowfalls.

The panorama is wonderful and from the Cinque Croci pass it is possible to enjoy a breathtaking view on the Cima d’Asta massif.
texts.long:
During the winter season, the hike to the Cinque Croci pass with mountain skis or snowshoes can be a thrilling experience.

After having parked at the Conseria bridge, in Val Campelle, it is possible to immediately wear the snowshoes and start walking.

The road, uphill but not significantly hard, venture into a fairy fir woods and then open on the Lagorai and on the Cima d’Asta massif, with a 360° view from the top.
texts.directions:
From the parking lot by the Consèria bridge (1465 m), follow the road to the Agritur Malga Casarina for about 100 m and then take a forest road on the left, until a hairpin turn. Here leave the forest road and reach a wide clearing (l’Aia del Buso) on the left side of the path, then keep walking until the hillside right under Malga Consèria. Then start walking to the alpine hut (1822 m), always open even during the winter.

From the hut, start walking uphill north-east to the Cinque Croci pass (2022 m), from where the view is just breathtaking. And now, hike north-west, on the Cima Socede slopes – paying attention to a few too steep stretches.

 

The return can be done on the same route as the climb or on the forest road that leads first to Malga Valsorda and then to the Consèria bridge.
texts.gettingThere:
From the SS47 of Valsugana (main road) exit at Castel Ivano (Strigno) - Valle del Tesino.

Reach the village of Strigno and turn towards Spera. Pass the village following the signs for Val Campelle.

Cross the whole valley on the main road until you reach Ponte Conseria, where you find the parking place.

Departing from the Malga Rolle (1,900 m), you descend to the starting point of the Paradiso chairlift from which you can clearly see the signs for the Colbricon lakes, path no. 348., moving to the top of the Paneveggio forest, with centuries-old red fir and larch trees and Cimbri pines. The return to Passo Rolle is via the same route.

logo.title: Hotel CYPRIANERHOF

texts.short:
Views: Great views to the Latemartowers, a wonderful view to the Rosengarten and Schlern.
Fascinating: famous rock buildings, legends of the Latemar and the lake of Carezza
texts.long: Transfer by bus to the Karerpass, 1740m. The hiking tour starts here and leads between forest and over the Latemar meadows up to the entrance into the small “Latemarscharte”. Here you are directly under the steep Latemar towers, approx. on 2000m. After a descent of 100 meters you will enter the "Labyrinth": an enormous rock break. Here the path leads us through the stones up and down finally to arrive on the timber line. At the end of the rock labyrinth the path descends to the “Mitterleger”, 1820m, a beautiful larch clearing with a forest hut and a spring. The way back leads you between the wonderful forest over the sea of Carezza. It goes further along the cross country ski route passing the hotel Moseralm on the sunny side of the Karerpass and on an easy ascent up to the Jolanda hut. From here you return by ski bus back to the Cyprianerhof.
